    bio: 'Hannah Arendt was born on October 14, 1906, in Linden, a district of Hanover, Germany, into a secular Jewish family. She studied philosophy at the University of Marburg under Martin Heidegger, with whom she had a brief but intellectually formative romantic relationship, before completing her doctorate under Karl Jaspers at Heidelberg in 1929 with a dissertation on the concept of love in Saint Augustine. The rise of Nazism forced her to flee Germany in 1933; she lived as a stateless refugee in Paris before emigrating to the United States in 1941, where she eventually became a citizen and built her academic career.\n\nArendt\'s major works reshaped political philosophy for the twentieth century and beyond. *The Origins of Totalitarianism* (1951) offered a sweeping analysis of anti-Semitism, imperialism, and the unprecedented nature of totalitarian rule. *The Human Condition* (1958) distinguished between labor, work, and action, arguing that political action — the capacity to begin something new in concert with others — is the highest expression of human freedom. Her controversial report on the trial of Adolf Eichmann, published as *Eichmann in Jerusalem: A Report on the Banality of Evil* (1963), introduced the concept of the "banality of evil," suggesting that radical evil can emerge not from monstrous intentions but from thoughtlessness and the failure to think critically.\n\nArendt held positions at the University of Chicago, the New School for Social Research, and other institutions, becoming one of the most influential public intellectuals of her era. She resisted being called a philosopher, preferring the term "political theorist," and her thought defied easy categorization — drawing on phenomenology, classical Greek thought, and her own experience as a refugee and witness to catastrophe. She died on December 4, 1975, in New York City, leaving behind an unfinished manuscript, *The Life of the Mind*, which explored the faculties of thinking, willing, and judging.',
